<li class="thin-divide-bottom comment neutral read"
  data-post-score="15"
  data-post-negative="-6"
  data-post-positive="21"
  data-post-id="26436705" data-poster-id="397931" id="comment-26436705">
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="bburdge"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=397931&amp;sid=1c0d8687a255636652201e5c1f474f6c">bburdge</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Scholae Palatinae</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/security/2014/03/phishing-page-hosted-on-google-a-true-dog-bites-man-scam/?comments=1&post=26436705#comment-26436705" title="2014-03-14T11:17:52-05:00" class="timeago datetime">Fri Mar 14, 2014 10:17 am</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      So, based on reading the original Symantec report here - these guys load a fake Google login page onto Google Drive, they then use the Google Drive tools to link it in an email, and when a recipient clicks the link it actually runs the fake login page - from the Google Drive server.<br /><br />I'm having a hard time understanding why this was ever possible, I doubt Google wants Drive to be a mini webserver, so why have web type pages (it's not clear from the description WHAT type of file they used) allowed to be actively viewable? This seems very open to abuse, and I can't think of what value it has for normal users.
      
    </div>
    <footer>
      <aside class="vote">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/ucp.php?mode=login&amp;return_to=http%3A%2F%2Farstechnica.com%2Fsecurity%2F2014%2F03%2Fphishing-page-hosted-on-google-a-true-dog-bites-man-scam%2F%3Fcomments%3D1%26amp%3Bstart%3D0%23comment-26436705" class="vote_login vote_up_login" title="Login to vote up">up</a>
