<li class="thin-divide-bottom comment star read"
  data-post-score="34"
  data-post-negative="0"
  data-post-positive="34"
  data-post-id="26436795" data-poster-id="397931" id="comment-26436795">
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="bburdge"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=397931&amp;sid=1c0d8687a255636652201e5c1f474f6c">bburdge</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Scholae Palatinae</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/security/2014/03/phishing-page-hosted-on-google-a-true-dog-bites-man-scam/?comments=1&post=26436795#comment-26436795" title="2014-03-14T11:27:49-05:00" class="timeago datetime">Fri Mar 14, 2014 10:27 am</a>
        
          <span class="highlight reader-fav">Reader Fav</span>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26436701#p26436701" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Spazmodica</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><span style="font-weight: bold">NEVER</span> click on links in emails, especially from unknown or seemingly &quot;official&quot; sources, and extra especially those that are requesting any form of login information!</div><br />That's easy to say, but not practical - for many people who may be using Google suite commercially it will not be uncommon for contacts to send them links to documents stored on Google Drive. <br /><br />And then when the Google login page comes up trying to access a document on Google Docs - that's not going to raise any red flags, it would be expected they ask for credentials to login to view the material, especially if there is some expectation that the material is restricted to certain people.<br /><br />This current one looks like a savvy user would have recognized it as bad (it doesn't mention that this one is spoofing a contact address, and a subject line of just &quot;Documents&quot; would be suspicious) however a more sophisticated attack using this same scheme would potentially catch even fairly alert users. If the attacker spoofs(or worse really uses) an already compromised account that had the victim in their contact list then the victim will believe it's a known person, and it comes up with a more reasonable subject line - &quot;Hey I wanted you to take a look at this.&quot; with some body text &quot;I put this together and I think it looks good, but I wanted to get your feedback before I put in the open.&quot; Then even someone who's somewhat cautious could believe it was legitimate.
      
    </div>
    <footer>
