<li class="thin-divide-bottom comment neutral read"
  data-post-score="18"
  data-post-negative="0"
  data-post-positive="18"
  data-post-id="26436831" data-poster-id="375631" id="comment-26436831">
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="therealeffingaeiouy"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=375631&amp;sid=1c0d8687a255636652201e5c1f474f6c">therealeffingaeiouy</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Scholae Palatinae</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/security/2014/03/phishing-page-hosted-on-google-a-true-dog-bites-man-scam/?comments=1&post=26436831#comment-26436831" title="2014-03-14T11:31:21-05:00" class="timeago datetime">Fri Mar 14, 2014 10:31 am</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      Not a phishing attempt but something recently I came across when renewing a family member's driver's license online.  Originally I went to the dps site on my phone but needed to switch over to my desktop.<br /><br />When I did I clicked on an ad (I believe, which by the way is crazy because I have done a ton of search advertising in the past) and clicked on renew.  I got halfway through the form of information for payment when I realized this was not the dps but a site that was essentially going to charge me $15 to link me to the dps page.<br /><br />To me this site was a flat out fraud.  I went back to the search results because google used to have a way to report ads, but I guess they decided it was too much of a hassle.  I should know better and I don't normally click on ads without knowing that is what I am doing.  Because I just did the search on my phone is rushed it on my desktop and looked for keywords.  Then the site specifically had a link for renewing your drivers license.  If I had not just been on the dps site and was a little less knowledgable I could easily see filling out their info and submitting it before realizing what happened.  <br /><br />You really got to double and triple check what site you are accessing whenever entering authentication information or any billing information.  I know all the scummy thing google advertisers have gotten away with over the years, but many people might think google is protecting them.  When it comes to advertising dollars, google is wholly reactionary.  They won't ban advertisers or behaviors unless they get complaints on the issue of enough volume they have to react.<br /><br />As it goes to phishing and mails.  I never click links in email unless it is some kind of verification check for a site I just signed up for.  Otherwise i am more than happy to go to the site normally.  Any information from a website that is important enough to send me an email to look at, is important enough to show me when I lot in as a normal user.  While checking the urls is obviously a good idea, just typing the site into your browser or clicking on a bookmark is even better.
      
    </div>
