    </header>
    <div class="body">
      I wonder how badly even 1Password would be fooled by this one. If you don't have it setup to specifically look for the <span style="font-weight: bold">accounts.</span>google.com subdomain, what's left for 1P to tell if the prompt is legit? The XSS dump to another domain should trigger an alarm, but that could be subsituted with a forum POST at some other google property.<br /><br />Edit: Furthermore, how does 2 factor protect against this? You're just giving the bad guy a tighter window to turn around pwnrship of your account. The fishee would get the password prompt, a 2 factor prompt that appears to fail, and then ANOTHER 2f prompt as the bad guy is going into account settings and turning 2f off. You would probably smell a skunk at that point, but it's too late. The only reason I see 2Factor not being pwned by this attack is because the returns on just hitting basic auth are good enough.<br /><br /><div style="padding: 3px;">
  <div style="margin-bottom: 3px; font-weight: bold;" onclick="var q = $(this).parent().find('.quotecontent > div');q.toggle();$(this).find('span').html(q.is(':visible')?'hide':'show');return false;">
    <b>Spoiler: </b>
    <span style="color: #FF5B00; cursor: pointer;">show</span>
  </div>
  <div class="quotecontent">
    <div style="display: none;">
      1GGb9mcVcyZ9WBsYc1U6dfCUqtPdJN6ygt
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
      
        <p class="edited">Last edited by <a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=109771&amp;sid=1c0d8687a255636652201e5c1f474f6c">pen_sq</a> on Fri Mar 14, 2014 11:31 am</p>
      
    </div>
