  data-post-score="22"
  data-post-negative="-2"
  data-post-positive="24"
  data-post-id="26437329" data-poster-id="331441" id="comment-26437329">
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="JGoat"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=331441&amp;sid=1c0d8687a255636652201e5c1f474f6c">JGoat</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Tribunus Militum</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/security/2014/03/phishing-page-hosted-on-google-a-true-dog-bites-man-scam/?comments=1&post=26437329#comment-26437329" title="2014-03-14T12:18:23-05:00" class="timeago datetime">Fri Mar 14, 2014 11:18 am</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      What sort of solution is &quot;Never click on links in emails&quot;?  That's ridiculously impractical.  I click links in emails all the time and have never suffered for it.  If it's suspicious, not from a trusted source, etc, then exercise caution, but this over-abundance of caution is unwarranted.  <br /><br />This phishing expedition is effective exactly because the &quot;NEVER click on links in emails&quot; approach is impractical.  Be wary of links in email, fine, 2-factor authentication, even better, but abstinence just doesn't work.
      
    </div>
