<li class="thin-divide-bottom comment neutral read"
  data-post-score="-2"
  data-post-negative="-12"
  data-post-positive="10"
  data-post-id="26437397" data-poster-id="330040" id="comment-26437397">
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="nibb"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=330040&amp;sid=1c0d8687a255636652201e5c1f474f6c">nibb</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Tribunus Militum</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/security/2014/03/phishing-page-hosted-on-google-a-true-dog-bites-man-scam/?comments=1&post=26437397#comment-26437397" title="2014-03-14T12:23:58-05:00" class="timeago datetime">Fri Mar 14, 2014 11:23 am</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      This is not clever at all, it just exploits Google owns stupidity by providing services using their own brand and domain and I was wondering why it took someone so long to figure out.<br /><br />Its common sense that any company providing any type of hosted services should never use its main company brand or domain to give public services to users.<br /><br />If Google uses their own domain or Google name in any part of their services, then they are going to be abused left and right in every possible way. This is why its an awful idea for them to even offer hosted pages and other mass media code execution from their servers using their domain.<br /><br />Now I donÂ´t mean they should not offer services on their servers, but they never should do it with the Google name on it which uses the google.com domain on it or even certificates that belong to the Google brand.<br /><br />Its a pretty dumb mistake and not something you would not expect from a huge company like Google.<br /><br />Microsoft never ever used the microsoft.com domain name for any customer facing services as far as I remember. The only bug they had, was with MSN accounts years back where you could register a <!-- e --><a href="mailto:youraccount@microsoft.com">youraccount@microsoft.com</a><!-- e -->, I did registered and had my own microsoft.com account, of course the email did not worked and you did not had actually email access, but in your MSN account you could actually make people think you had a Microsoft ID, it did for fun but someone else could had exploited that for impersonation of Microsoft staff.<br /><br />Same story, different approach. Google should keep their domain name separated from public hosted files.<br /><br />Now Google is going to face this problem and similar even more as they centralized their brand under the Google umbrella. Even Amazon uses different names and domains for their services separated from the official Amazon brand.<br /><br />Now any of this companies that offer public hosted files, pages, etc, will need to invest in a huge abuse team if they want to deal with this issues, because as services become more centralized, malware authors are going to use more hosted services, Dropbox, Google, etc to host their malicious code.<br /><br />Today some server attacks and hosted malware is already coming from Amazon Cloud services, IÂ´m starting to see more and more attacks coming from amazon ec2 domains which means malware authors are starting to try to hide themselves between massive popular services.
      
        <p class="edited">Last edited by <a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=330040&amp;sid=1c0d8687a255636652201e5c1f474f6c">nibb</a> on Fri Mar 14, 2014 11:27 am</p>
      
    </div>
