<li class="thin-divide-bottom comment neutral read"
  data-post-score="10"
  data-post-negative="0"
  data-post-positive="10"
  data-post-id="26437479" data-poster-id="395395" id="comment-26437479">
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="twocows"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=395395&amp;sid=1c0d8687a255636652201e5c1f474f6c">twocows</a></span><span class="rank">Wise, Aged Ars Veteran</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/security/2014/03/phishing-page-hosted-on-google-a-true-dog-bites-man-scam/?comments=1&post=26437479#comment-26437479" title="2014-03-14T12:31:09-05:00" class="timeago datetime">Fri Mar 14, 2014 11:31 am</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      I consider myself a journeyman when it comes to security knowledge (I work in IT and actively research security, but I'm by no means an expert), but this would have fooled me if I had clicked on it (I wouldn't have, but that's besides the point). Aside from the unsolicited email, this doesn't set off any of my flags. I generally check the sender in the header details, the URL, what I'm logging into, and whether the SSL certificate is valid. The fact that it's logging into Google drive wouldn't have set my alarms off because, to me, it seems perfectly reasonable that a document might be hosted on Google drive. It doesn't sound like any of those other tests failed, either. The only giveaway (and it should be the most obvious, but you know people) was that it was an unsolicited email, but I do IT for a payroll company where people often need to respond to unsolicited email to stay current on tax law or to be ready to respond to clients or whatever.<br /><br />This was really well done. I'm hoping this was targeted because if this was a drive-by, it's one of the best drive-bys I've seen in a while.
      
        <p class="edited">Last edited by <a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=395395&amp;sid=1c0d8687a255636652201e5c1f474f6c">twocows</a> on Fri Mar 14, 2014 11:35 am</p>
      
