    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26437329#p26437329" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">JGoat</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">What sort of solution is &quot;Never click on links in emails&quot;?  That's ridiculously impractical.  I click links in emails all the time and have never suffered for it.  If it's suspicious, not from a trusted source, etc, then exercise caution, but this over-abundance of caution is unwarranted.  <br /><br />This phishing expedition is effective exactly because the &quot;NEVER click on links in emails&quot; approach is impractical.  Be wary of links in email, fine, 2-factor authentication, even better, but abstinence just doesn't work.</div><br /><br />Let's bring back <span style="font-weight: bold">email signing</span> with a vengeance. <a href="http://www.comodo.com/home/email-security/free-email-certificate.php" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Comodo is still offering <span style="font-weight: bold">free email signing certificates</span></a>â€¦ If you don't want to type the URL, just search Google for &quot;free email signing certificate&quot;. I've tried Comodo's email signing certificates and they seem to work fine. I might click links in <span style="font-style: italic">signed emails</span>, but otherwise, <span style="font-style: italic">never</span>, unless it's a confirmation email that comes from an expected source within the expected ten second time-frame after I've visited the sender's website already!
      
    </div>
