<li class="thin-divide-bottom comment neutral read"
  data-post-score="2"
  data-post-negative="0"
  data-post-positive="2"
  data-post-id="26437791" data-poster-id="271803" id="comment-26437791">
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="matthewslyman"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=271803&amp;sid=1c0d8687a255636652201e5c1f474f6c">matthewslyman</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Scholae Palatinae</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/security/2014/03/phishing-page-hosted-on-google-a-true-dog-bites-man-scam/?comments=1&post=26437791#comment-26437791" title="2014-03-14T12:58:16-05:00" class="timeago datetime">Fri Mar 14, 2014 11:58 am</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26437545#p26437545" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">twocows</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26437489#p26437489" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">matthewslyman</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26437329#p26437329" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">JGoat</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">What sort of solution is &quot;Never click on links in emails&quot;?  That's ridiculously impractical.  I click links in emails all the time and have never suffered for it.  If it's suspicious, not from a trusted source, etc, then exercise caution, but this over-abundance of caution is unwarranted.  <br />This phishing expedition is effective exactly because the &quot;NEVER click on links in emails&quot; approach is impractical.  Be wary of links in email, fine, 2-factor authentication, even better, but abstinence just doesn't work.</div><br />Let's bring back <span style="font-weight: bold">email signing</span> with a vengeance. <a href="http://www.comodo.com/home/email-security/free-email-certificate.php" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Comodo is still offering <span style="font-weight: bold">free email signing certificates</span></a>â€¦ If you don't want to type the URL, just search Google for &quot;free email signing certificate&quot;. I've tried Comodo's email signing certificates and they seem to work fine. I might click links in <span style="font-style: italic">signed emails</span>, but otherwise, <span style="font-style: italic">never</span>, unless it's a confirmation email that comes from an expected source within the expected ten second time-frame after I've visited the sender's website already!</div><br />This is interesting. How does this work, specifically? I don't know much about email, myself. Are they using PGP? I thought PGP required support on both ends. If that's not the case, how is this implemented? I'd look for details on my own, but since I don't know how they're implementing this or what protocol they're using, I don't know what to search for to begin with.</div><br /><a href="http://www.comodo.com/support/products/email_certs/index.php" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Just try it!</a> The only thing I'd be wary of is that this works much better with Thunderbird than with Outlook. (Recent versions of MS Outlook on recent versions of Windows can freeze when cryptographically signing emails â€” I can't remember why, but I seem to recall that the error messages I saw suggested it has something to do with new security mechanisms built in to more recent versions of Windows for managing cryptographic certificates.) You don't need to set this up on both ends, in fact, the functionality to read/display these signatures is built in to all major email clients: Outlook, Thunderbird etc. It works because the recipient's computer already trusts Comodo (who have the root certificate), and Comodo verifies as part of their certificate issuing process that you control the email account for which the certificate is valid (your new certificate is based on Comodo's root, which is pre-installed on a wide variety of operating systems etc.) Signed emails seem to make it through spam filters just as easily as unsigned emails, so no problems there. The signature typically only takes a few extra kB in size for each email.
      
    </div>
    <footer>
