<li class="thin-divide-bottom comment neutral read"
  data-post-score="11"
  data-post-negative="-1"
  data-post-positive="12"
  data-post-id="26437897" data-poster-id="188698" id="comment-26437897">
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="kruzes"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=188698&amp;sid=1c0d8687a255636652201e5c1f474f6c">kruzes</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Scholae Palatinae</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/security/2014/03/phishing-page-hosted-on-google-a-true-dog-bites-man-scam/?comments=1&post=26437897#comment-26437897" title="2014-03-14T13:10:53-05:00" class="timeago datetime">Fri Mar 14, 2014 12:10 pm</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      Where I'd be suspicious is that, being a Gmail user, I'm already logged in viewing the email, and I expect the username to be filled already, even when Google asks me for the password.<br /><br />But this is really, really clever and very well done. Regrettably.<br /><br />Also, there seems to be a misconception here. Two-factor doesn't prevent your password from being stolen. It won't even warn you that your password was stolen. The way this is construed, you're always presented with a fake login page hosted on Google (Drive). Regardless of what you put into the fake form, you're always redirected to a valid, public document on Google Drive. The attackers collect the account data, right or wrong. If you have two-factor, that won't be enough for them to get into your account, but they'll have your password anyway.
      
    </div>
    <footer>
      <aside class="vote">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/ucp.php?mode=login&amp;return_to=http%3A%2F%2Farstechnica.com%2Fsecurity%2F2014%2F03%2Fphishing-page-hosted-on-google-a-true-dog-bites-man-scam%2F%3Fcomments%3D1%26amp%3Bstart%3D0%23comment-26437897" class="vote_login vote_up_login" title="Login to vote up">up</a>
        (
        <span class="vote-total pos">+11</span>
        | +<span class="vote-positive">12</span> / <span class="vote-negative">-1</span>
        )
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/ucp.php?mode=login&amp;return_to=http%3A%2F%2Farstechnica.com%2Fsecurity%2F2014%2F03%2Fphishing-page-hosted-on-google-a-true-dog-bites-man-scam%2F%3Fcomments%3D1%26amp%3Bstart%3D0%23comment-26437897" class="vote_login vote_down_login" title="Login to vote down">down</a>
        
