<li class="thin-divide-bottom comment neutral read"
  data-post-score="1"
  data-post-negative="0"
  data-post-positive="1"
  data-post-id="26437935" data-poster-id="66588" id="comment-26437935">
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="ojintoad"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=66588&amp;sid=1c0d8687a255636652201e5c1f474f6c">ojintoad</a></span><span class="rank">Smack-Fu Master, in training</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/security/2014/03/phishing-page-hosted-on-google-a-true-dog-bites-man-scam/?comments=1&post=26437935#comment-26437935" title="2014-03-14T13:14:07-05:00" class="timeago datetime">Fri Mar 14, 2014 12:14 pm</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      Is this something that a password manager like LastPass would be good for?<br /><br />If LastPass is properly configured with the correct domains for filling in usernames/passwords, would it suggest the username/password for this form?  If so, then perhaps that's an improvement LastPass could make.  If not, then perhaps considering why your password manager isn't filling in your account info might be a good tip off to double check what you're logging in to.
      
    </div>
