    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26437329#p26437329" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">JGoat</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">What sort of solution is &quot;Never click on links in emails&quot;?  That's ridiculously impractical.  I click links in emails all the time and have never suffered for it.  If it's suspicious, not from a trusted source, etc, then exercise caution, but this over-abundance of caution is unwarranted.  <br /><br />This phishing expedition is effective exactly because the &quot;NEVER click on links in emails&quot; approach is impractical.  Be wary of links in email, fine, 2-factor authentication, even better, but abstinence just doesn't work.</div><br /><br />What are you talking about? Abstinence works perfectly, 100% of the time. You can never be fooled by a fake link if you never click on a fake link.<br /><br />If you <span style="font-style: italic">can't be abstinent</span> that's a different problem.
      
